<p><b>Q. Why shouldn’t I declare bankruptcy? Wouldn’t that get rid of all my debt?</b></p>
<p>
A. Sometimes it feels like your debt is so insurmountable that your only option is bankruptcy. But you should be careful before making that choice. Bankruptcy will affect your credit for years to come. It can result in loss of property and you still may be forced to pay off the debts.</p>
<p>
Here’s what to expect if you choose to declare bankruptcy:<p>
<p>- Bankruptcy can destroy your credit by leaving your ratings low for as long as 7 to 10 years.</p>
<p>- Chapter 7 bankruptcy can require the sale of any property not protected by law.</p>
<p>- Chapter 13 bankruptcy will offer a payment plan and will leave a bankruptcy mark on your credit report.</p>
<p>- Your credit report will reflect the bankruptcy option you chose, and your chances of getting credit will be low if not impossible and the interest rates will be high.</p>

